The Khenari: Keepers of the Ninth Descent

Transcribed from the testimony archive of Silence Court Twelve,
Akh'enet District, by permit of the Reed Ledger Wardens

They come from Akh'enet, the mortuary-legal civilization that
once administered passage between life and death for half the known
world. Jackal-headed, tall, precise in speech and motion. Their eyes
hold a steady amber light that does not waver, even in darkness.

To the Khenari, death is not tragedy. Death is transaction. A
death unrecorded collapses inheritance chains, destabilizes road-law,
and opens gaps in the civic record through which disputes and false
claims pour like water. The dead have rights. The living have
obligations to document the transfer.

Their sacred object is the death-ledger — not a book of sorrow
but a book of lawful completion. Every entry represents a life
accounted for, a passage verified, a chain of descent preserved.

Their theology follows the Doctrine of Ninth Descent: nine
stages of lawful passage from life to death, each requiring witness,
each carrying specific legal consequence. To die outside the Doctrine
is not sin — it is clerical catastrophe.

The silence courts are where testimony is clarified. Stone
chambers designed for acoustic deprivation, where a witness hears
only their own voice and the questions of the adjudicator. Truth,
the Khenari hold, is easier to find when the world stops shouting.

The Bellwind Collapse scattered them from Akh'enet across the
lands. Now they are found wherever death-records are valued — in
Midgaard's courts, in Kowloon's registries, at crossroads where
the unrecorded dead accumulate.

They are incorruptible notaries. This is not metaphor. A Khenari
who falsifies a death-record is considered to have died — socially,
legally, in every way that matters to their people.

Watch the tail. The face reveals nothing, but the tail betrays
emotion — a sharp flick for anger, a low curl for grief, a
stillness that means the Khenari is deciding something you will
not enjoy.

Three factions endure among them: the Reed Ledger Wardens, who
maintain the old records and seek to rebuild Akh'enet's archives;
the Moon Sepulchrists, who tend the dead in foreign lands and
adapt the Doctrine to local custom; and the Salt Jackal
Reclaimers, who hunt for death-records lost in the Collapse and
are not gentle about recovering them.

They will record your death with perfect accuracy.
They consider this a kindness.
